---
/**
 * Principle — "the agent is an untrusted process" manifesto paragraph.
 * Draws from PHILOSOPHY.md. Single-column prose, big headline with one
 * cyan accent phrase.
 */
interface Props {
  githubUrl: string;
}
const { githubUrl } = Astro.props;
---
<section class="border-b border-white/5">
  <div class="mx-auto max-w-7xl px-6 py-24 sm:py-32">
    <div class="max-w-3xl">
      <p data-reveal class="mb-4 text-[11px] font-medium uppercase tracking-[0.22em] text-white/55">
        The principle
      </p>
      <h2
        data-reveal
        class="mb-10 text-4xl font-bold leading-[1.05] tracking-[-0.015em] text-white sm:text-5xl md:text-6xl"
        style="font-family: 'Outfit', 'Inter Variable', sans-serif;"
      >
        The agent is
        <span class="text-cyan-400">an untrusted process.</span>
      </h2>
      <div data-reveal class="space-y-6 text-[17px] leading-[1.65] text-white/65">
        <p>
          For 50 years, software engineering ceremony &mdash; version control, code review,
          blame, audit logs &mdash; assumed one thing: the writer of the code is a human you
          can hold accountable. That assumption silently broke when AI agents started
          writing the majority of new code.
        </p>
        <p>
          Agents fail in ways human contributors never would. They silently delete tests.
          They rewrite mocks to make themselves pass. They refactor across boundaries
          without understanding intent. A bad decision at 14:32:07 is 200 files deep by
          14:32:42. None of the tools in your stack &mdash; git, your editor, your CI &mdash; were
          designed for that.
        </p>
        <p class="text-white">
          Treat AI coding agents the way a security engineer treats any process with
          write access to your filesystem: assume it will eventually do something
          wrong, and build the controls that let you recover when it does.
        </p>
        <p>
          <code class="font-mono text-cyan-400">au</code> is the substrate.
          Observability, attribution, reversibility &mdash; the three primitives the next
          decade of agent-aware tooling will be built on.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div data-reveal class="mt-10">
        <a
          href={`${githubUrl}/blob/main/PHILOSOPHY.md`}
          rel="noopener"
          class="inline-flex items-center gap-2 text-sm text-white/65 underline decoration-white/20 underline-offset-4 hover:text-white hover:decoration-white/50"
        >
          Read the full essay
          <svg class="h-3.5 w-3.5" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round">
            <path d="M5 12h14M13 5l7 7-7 7" />
          </svg>
        </a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>
